January 6th was a test of American democracy, but the fair trials of those responsible will further demonstrate this Nation’s commitment to the rule of law and hold accountable those who attempted to undermine it.

Today’s charges are consistent with those the Select Committee referred to the Special Counsel last year, and successful prosecutions will not only bring accountability but also help prevent something like January 6th from ever happening again.

And, at the end of its investigation, the bipartisan January 6th Select Committee turned over to the Justice Department its evidence of an extensive plot by the ex-President to overturn the Presidential election on January 6th and prevent the peaceful transfer of power.
Those heroes asked us for something in that hearing: Hold those responsible for that deadly attack accountable.

Two years ago, when I chaired the first Select Committee hearing, I was moved by the courageous testimony of four brave police officers who came to the defense of the Capitol and American democracy on January 6, 2021.

This plan would have provided much-needed relief to millions of struggling Americans who are burdened with the crippling weight of student loan debt.
This relief could have been a significant stimulus to our economy, helping create jobs and a more prosperous future for all.

I find the Supreme Court’s decision to halt President Biden’s student loan forgiveness plan extremely disappointing. The burden of student debt poses a serious obstacle to students and their families who are attempting to improve their lives and create better futures.

Without this factor, our colleges and universities are in danger of becoming more homogeneous and not reflective of the true diversity that exists in our society. We must find ways to promote educational fairness and equity while upholding the importance of an inclusive society.

In many cases, college admissions consideration of a student's race is an important factor in ensuring that historically disadvantaged students can access the same educational opportunities available to their more privileged peers.
I am deeply disappointed by the decision of the Supreme Court.
